20 October!!
This RSI poster of Gino Boccasile depicts the massacre of 184 children and 20 school's personell, during a mistaken American raid over Milan. On 20 October 1944, 80 t of bombs landed on the innocent district of Gorla, while one bomb scored a hit inside the stairwell of Elementary School "Francesco Crispi", destroying the entire building and buring all the kids.
The district of Gorla had no military relevance.

EL ALAMEIN Day 8
On 30 October the fate of the battle was already decided, the remaining Italo-German  forces could only delay the end and avoid the complete annihilation. That day one Italian cistern brought 600 t of fuel, amounting to 1 day of usage for the entire Panzer Corp. The ammunitions stock remained equally critical during the whole battle, making the extensive use of italian artillery impossible.

EL ALAMEIN Day 6
On 28 October in North sector the Trento division sustained a heavy attack from the 1st South African and 4th Indian division. Today was recorded the last real italo/german counterattack to stabilize the northern lines. 
By the end of the day the British had still 800 tanks in operation (with great presence of better performing american tanks), while the axis forces could rely on 80 German tanks and 197 italian tanks (only on paper).

EL ALAMEIN Day 4
On 26 October Rommel ordered back the 21.Panzer Division in the North sector: realizing that the Folgore and Pavia division could repel every british offensive without panzer support, Rommel could turn the tide of the battle with an aimed counterattack in North, against the British bridgehead, making use of the entire tank Corp (21.Panzer Division, 15.Panzer Division and Divisione Corazzata Littorio). At 3:00 Folgore Division faced the third offensive in its sector: the 7th, 44th and 50th Infantry British Divisions attacked the paratroopers positions, while 1st Free French Brigade and Greek Brigade tried an encirclement.

EL ALAMEIN Day 3
25 October the second attack of XIII Army Corp, under the command of General Horrocks, failed to expell the Folgore division from the south heights, despite the help of 160 tanks from the 1st Armoured Division: within 3 days of offensive, the british division had already lost 200 tanks.
The XXX Army Corp North gained some ground in axis minefields and entire Italo-German units were destroyed: once again the advance was contained with great effort of 15. Panzer Division. At the end of the day the Germans could rely only on 31 tanks.

EL ALAMEIN Day 2
In the morning of 24 October 1942 the first counterattacks were launched by Italo-German forces: in North sector the 15th Panzer Division and Divisione Corazzata Littorio repelled the advancing infantry British division, engaging a harsh battle with the 1st Armoured Division (around 100 tanks). In south sector the Folgore division attacked with the Ariete support , and before the dawn 31 British tanks were destroyed and the front line partially restored near Munassib. The battle was now on a standstill, while the allies had advanced only 9.7 km in north, the axis had already worned its armoured division and nearly dried the fuel shortages.

Exactly 78 years ago, 23 October 1942 at 21:40 started the Second Battle of El Alamein with a 1.000-gun barrage from British lines. In 15 minutes around 500.000 shells landed on the first Italo-German lines. After 13 days of desperate fight, the Italian armoured divisions Littorio and Ariete were virtually annihilated, losing nearly 270 medium tanks and Semoventi.
Today the Ariete division survive as 132° Armoured Brigade "Ariete".

Lined up Sturmpanzers IV Brummbar in Littoria, Italy 1944. This group of tanks belonged to Sturmpanzerabteilung 216, transferred in Italy against the allied beachhead of Anzio with only 28 active tanks. All the surviving Brummbars in 1945 were all blown up near Lago di Garda to prevent capture.
